data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically in .NET 8.

**No migration is needed** for Thread.Abort concerns. This code will compile and run on .NET 8 as-is.

That said, a modern .NET 8 approach would replace manual threads with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll` for cleaner concurrency:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        await Task.Delay(100, ct);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

This gives you built-in cancellation support via `CancellationToken` if you need it later.
